    • \(Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{1i}+ \beta_2 X_{2i}+ \beta_3 X_{3i}+ \beta_4 X_{4i}+ \beta_5 X_{5i}+ \beta_6 X_{6i}+ \beta_7 X_{7i}+ \beta_8 X_{8i}+ u_i\), where:
      • \(Y_i\): dichotomous measure of whether student \(i\) in participated in internship/co-op in 2005-06
      • \(X_{1i}\): (continuous) high school reading test score
      • \(X_{2i}\): (continuous) measure of parental income
      • \(X_{3i}\): (dichotomous) student \(i\) identifies as female
      • \(X_{4i}\): (dichotomous) student \(i\) identifies as Asian or Pacific Islander (API)
      • \(X_{5i}\): (dichotomous) student \(i\) identifies as Black
      • \(X_{6i}\): (dichotomous) student \(i\) identifies as Latinx
      • \(X_{7i}\): (dichotomous) student \(i\) identifies as Native American
      • \(X_{8i}\): (dichotomous) student \(i\) identifies as two or more races
      • \(u_i\) is all variables that affect \(Y_i\) but were not included in our model
  • OLS prediction line
    • without estimates
      • \(\hat{Y_i} = \hat{\beta_0} + \hat{\beta_1}X_i + \hat{\beta_2} X_{2i}+ \hat{\beta_3} X_{3i}+ \hat{\beta_4} X_{4i}+ \hat{\beta_5} X_{5i}+ \hat{\beta_6} X_{6i}+ \hat{\beta_7} X_{7i}+ \hat{\beta_8} X_{8i}\)
    • with estimates
      • \(\hat{Y_i} =\) 1.1411 + -0.0015 \(\times X_{1i}\) + 0 \(\times X_{2i}\) + -0.0047 \(\times X_{3i}\) + 0.0062 \(\times X_{4i}\) + 0.0177 \(\times X_{5i}\) + -0.0117 \(\times X_{6i}\) + 0.0472 \(\times X_{7i}\) + 0.0247 \(\times X_{8i}\)


Interpreting Linear Probability Model, Continuous X

  • Dependent variable is a 0/1 measure of whether student participated in an internship
  • Interpretation of \(\hat{\beta_k}\)
    • Generic:
      • On average, a one-unit increase in X is associated with a \(\hat{\beta_k}*100\) percentage point change in the probability of Y=1
    • Interpretation for \(X_{1i}\) (high school reading test score); \(\hat{\beta_1}=\) -0.0015
      • on average, a one-point increase in high school reading test score is associated with a -0.1463 percentage-point change in the probability of having an internship.
      • that is, this is a decline in probability of receiving an internship that is less than one percentage point.
  • Interpretation of \(\hat{\beta_k}\) when you SCALE X
    • Generic:
      • On average, a N-unit increase in X is associated with a ((N-unit\(*\hat{\beta_1}\))*100) percentage point change in the probability of Y=1
    • Interpretation for a 10-point increase in \(X_{1i}\) (high school reading test score); \(\hat{\beta_1}=\) -0.0015
      • on average, a 10-point increase in high school reading test score is associated with a -1.4631 percentage-point change in the probability of having an internship.
      • that is, this is about a 1.5 percentage point decline in probability of receiving an internship (e.g., from 50.0% to 48.5% probability of receiving an internship; or going from a 30% to 28.5% chance of receiving an internship.


Linear Probability Model, with Categorical X

  • Dependent variable is a 0/1 measure of whether student participated in an internship
  • Interpretation of \(\hat{\beta_1}\)
    • Generic: being in the “non-reference group” as opposed to the “reference group” is, on average, associated with a \(100*\hat{\beta_1}\) percentage point change in the probability of Y=1
  • Interpretation for \(X_{8i}\) (0/1 student identies as two or more races); \(\hat{\beta_8}\) 0.0247
    • (reference group is “identifies as white”)
    • identifying as two-or-more races as opposed to identifying as white is, on avarage, associated with 2.4676 percentage-point change in the probability of having an internship.
    • that is, this about a 2.5% increase in the probability of having an internship (e.g., from 20% to 22.5% probability of having an internship)



Interpretation of results from journal articles


Cabrera, N. L., Milem, J. F., Jaquette, O., & Marx, R. (2014). Missing the (student achievement) forest for all the (political) trees: Empiricism and the Mexican American Studies controversy in Tucson. American Educational Research Journal, 51(6), 1084-1118.


Below is partial screenshot from Table 3 from, where:

  • \(Y\) = 0/1 student graduated from high school
  • \(X_1\) = 0/1 student participated in the Mexican American Studies (MAS) major


And below is text interpreting results

  • note that the regression coefficient of 0.095 was interpreted as, participating in MAS as opposed to not participating in MAS was, on average, associated with a 9.5 percentage point increase in the probability of graduattion
    • where the 9.5 is calculated as follows: \(\hat{\beta_1}*100 = .095 * 100 = 9.5\)
